    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of <i>Malacothamnus fasciculatus</i> includes the Central California Coast (261A) and Central California Coast Ranges (M262A).</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Ac). A stand of <i>Malacothamnus aboriginum</i> was sampled in Pine Canyon of the Diablo Range.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Ba-b, Bd-j). Stands from the Santa Monica Mountains (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006) characterize the alliance. They are likely to occur in other low-elevation subsections. Stands have been sampled on Santa Catalina Island (Dixon et al. )</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Ba-d, Bf-g, Bj-l, Bn-o). Stands sampled in western Riverside Co. occur on slopes adjacent to coastal scrub and chaparral (Klein and Evens 2005). Others are likely to occur in other low-elevation subsections.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Stands represent post-fire conditions in many parts of California shrublands. Even though this vegetation type is adapted to rapid reseeding and establishment, very high fire frequencies (< 10-year return interval) would reduce seed banks and potentially eliminate the alliance from the landscape. </div>
</div>

    

    

